# Overfitting in Machine Learning
This note explains what **overfitting** is, why it is dangerous in real-world machine learning, and how to detect and prevent it.
---
## Conclusion
Overfitting happens when a machine learning model learns **noise** instead of the **true patterns** in the data.
A model that only memorizes past data cannot make reliable predictions for the future.
---
## Why Overfitting Is a Problem
An overfitted model performs very well on training data,  
but fails on **new, unseen data**.
This makes it useless for real business decisions, where we always deal with future data.
---
## What Is Overfitting?
Overfitting occurs when a model is **too complex for the amount of data**.
Instead of learning general relationships,  
the model memorizes individual training examples.
---
##  Example (Demand Forecasting)
A demand forecasting model may perfectly match historical sales.  
However, if it has learned random fluctuations instead of real demand patterns,  
it will fail to predict future sales correctly.
---
## How to Detect Overfitting
- Compare training and validation performance  
- Use cross-validation  
- Monitor error metrics such as RMSE  
If training accuracy is high but validation accuracy is low, overfitting is likely happening.
---
##  How to Reduce Overfitting
- Use simpler models  
- Add regularization  
- Increase training data  
- Apply proper feature selection  
---
## Why It Matters for ML Engineers
ML engineers must ensure that models **generalize well to new data**.
Preventing overfitting is essential for building **trustworthy and usable prediction systems** in real businesses.
---
##  What I Learned
High accuracy on training data does **not** mean a model is good.
A truly good model is one that performs well on **unseen data**.
---

